Design Patterns – Summary (Points)

* Design Pattern is a reusable solution to common software design problems.
* It helps create maintainable, reusable, scalable, and flexible software.
* Design patterns provide best practices and a common way to solve recurring design issues.
* They improve communication among developers by using standard design concepts.

Types of Design Patterns

1. Creational Patterns

* Focus on object creation.
* Make object creation flexible and independent of concrete classes.
* Examples:

  * Singleton: Only one instance of a class.
  * Factory: Creates objects without specifying their exact class.
  * Builder: Builds complex objects step by step.

2. Structural Patterns

* Focus on combining classes and objects.
* Help different components work together efficiently.
* Examples:

  * Adapter: Makes incompatible interfaces compatible.
  * Decorator: Adds new functionality dynamically.
  * Facade: Provides a simple interface to a complex system.

3. Behavioral Patterns

* Focus on communication and interaction between objects.
* Define how responsibilities are shared among objects.
* Examples:

  * Observer: Notifies all registered objects when data changes.
  * Strategy: Allows selecting different algorithms at runtime.
  * Command: Encapsulates requests as command objects.

Common Design Patterns

* Singleton: Ensures only one object instance exists.
* Factory: Creates objects without exposing creation logic.
* Builder: Constructs complex objects step by step.
* Adapter: Connects incompatible interfaces.
* Decorator: Dynamically extends object functionality.
* Observer: Automatically updates dependent objects.
* Strategy: Switches algorithms during runtime.
* Facade: Simplifies access to complex subsystems.
* MVC: Separates an application into Model, View, and Controller.
* MVVM: Uses a ViewModel to separate UI from business logic and supports data binding.

Benefits of Design Patterns

* Improve code reusability.
* Increase maintainability.
* Enhance flexibility and scalability.
* Reduce tight coupling.
* Encourage clean architecture and best coding practices.
* Simplify software development and maintenance.
